# pyforthegirls — Canon

Last updated: April 26, 2026.

## What actually happened

**Tegan Ashby was planning to fake her death.**

- 17 years old at time of disappearance, closeted lesbian, suicidal in spring 2004
- Decided to fake a death rather than complete suicide
- Plan: vanish from camp on Aug 14, 2004; relocate to the East Coast; start a new life under a new identity
- The plan was driven by a 17-year-old’s inability to legally leave Alberta. Three more months and she’d have been 18 and could have walked out. She didn’t have three months.
- Built infrastructure since spring: the laptop-as-cipher journal, password-protected diary architecture, learning Python deliberately
- The Python game the player is playing IS what Tegan made — a forwarding mechanism designed to reveal her safe-arrival info to anyone who cared enough to learn the language she was learning
- She fell for Wren in the middle of the plan. The Wren entanglement complicated her exit. She did not abandon the plan.

**Tyler killed her.**

- Tyler is a boy at camp, an ordinary teenage Albertan
- Tegan kissed Wren in front of Tyler at the bonfire (early August), ostensibly as a joke for him, secretly because she wanted to and the social cover of “performing for the boy” let her
- Tyler took the kiss as encouragement initially. Sometime between the bonfire and Aug 14, Tyler started suspecting he was being used. The boathouse on Aug 14 confirmed it.
- **The Aug 14 sequence:**
  - Earlier on Aug 14: Tegan tells Wren she’s leaving camp / going home early. Wren asks to meet at the boathouse to talk her out of it.
  - Tegan writes her last diary entry at 9:31 PM in her cabin: “i told her i was going to leave camp… she said meet me at the boathouse tonight.” She leaves the laptop in her cabin and brings only her flip phone.
  - Tegan goes to the boathouse around 10-11 PM. Wren is there. They hook up.
  - **Tyler is also already there, hiding.** He’d been watching, jealous and suspicious after the bonfire. He sees Tegan and Wren together — physically — confirming Tegan used him as a beard.
  - After the hookup, Tegan tells Wren something like “i’m going to stay a few more minutes, i need to think.” Wren leaves for her cabin around 23:34 (just before her 23:42 alibi-refining AIM with Briar — the “study session” message).
  - Tegan, alone at the boathouse, texts Hannah on her flip phone: “she wants me to meet her at the boathouse at 11” (referring to the *ride* Hannah arranged), then “left rosewood. heading down” (covering for the fact that she’s still at the boathouse not back at cabin), then “she’s not here yet” / “STILL not here” as the ride is late.
  - Tyler waits ~10 minutes after Wren leaves to be sure she’s not coming back. He emerges at 23:44. Tegan sees him approach: “wait. someone’s coming up the path. it’s not her.”
  - Tyler kills Tegan around 23:46 as she’s typing the next text — which gets one letter out: “h” (the start of “Hannah,” her friend, her contact, the only person who could call for help).
  - Tyler drops Tegan’s flip phone in Kettle Lake. Phone is never recovered.
  - Tyler also disposes of Tegan’s body. Method TBD — possibly weighted and sunk, possibly into the woods.
- **Wren has no idea any of this happened after she left.** Wren walked away from the boathouse around 23:34 and went straight to her cabin to AIM with Briar. Her last memory of Tegan is alive, telling her she’d think about staying. Wren genuinely believes Tegan ran away that night, possibly back to her cabin, possibly home — Wren doesn’t know.

**What Wren is covering up:**

- Wren’s alibi-building with Briar on Aug 14 is real, but it’s covering an **inappropriate sexual relationship with a junior counsellor**, not a murder. Wren is 19 and Tegan is 17; if anyone knew Wren had been at the boathouse that night, Wren would lose her job and be reported, possibly criminally.
- Next morning Tegan is gone. Camp goes into search mode. Wren can’t say “I was with her at the boathouse last night” without copping to the affair. So she sticks to her alibi: in the cabin, with Briar.
- **Wren has spent a year unable to grieve openly, unable to say what she knows, unable to volunteer that she was the last person to see Tegan alive — because doing so would expose the predation.** Her silence is for self-preservation, not because she killed anyone.
- The “i’m not okay tegan” crack in her email is real. Wren genuinely loved Tegan in her own broken way.

**What Hannah is covering up:**

- Hannah arranged Tegan’s escape ride. Hannah’s last message from Tegan was “h.”
- Hannah waited for confirmation that never came. After hours of silence she would have realized something went wrong — but she didn’t know what.
- Hannah may not even know Tegan disappeared. She might think Tegan got cold feet and never followed through. She might have heard later via Google or news that Tegan was reported missing from camp, or she might not have. It depends on whether Tegan’s disappearance made enough news to reach Halifax.
- Either way, Hannah can’t speak up. To do so would cop to **planning to help a 17-year-old fake her death and run away** — interstate (interprovincial) conspiracy, identity-related crimes, harboring a minor runaway. Hannah’s silence is for self-preservation too.
- Hannah’s grief is uncertain in a specific way: she doesn’t know if Tegan ran on her own, was caught, was killed, or made it out via a different mechanism. She’s been carrying this alone for a year.

**The phone, the SMS log, and the laptop:**

- Tegan’s flip phone is what she used at the boathouse on Aug 14. Phone is in Kettle Lake.
- Tegan had set up her phone to BCC every outgoing SMS to her own hotmail address. Framed in-game as: counsellors weren’t supposed to have phones, so she was being careful. (The deeper reason — preparation for vanishing — is not foregrounded in Ch1-3 and shouldn’t be.)
- Tegan’s laptop stayed in her cabin on Aug 14. The diary timestamp is 9:31 PM, written before she went to the boathouse. **No one edited the diary file. No Wren-edits-diary subplot.** The diary is genuine Tegan, written before going to meet Wren, with the keyword-encoded “her name is wren halloway” repetitions baked in.
- The Ch2 realization beat says “wren has been on this account… she didn’t make new entries, she edited tegan’s.” This still works for OTHER files Wren might have edited (e.g., chat logs after Tegan disappeared, the Aug 15+ files in the zip that show Tegan’s “active” account post-mortem). But the Aug 14 diary specifically wasn’t edited.

**Hannah is Glorfindel.**

- Real name: Hannah
- Screen name: glorfindel_lives
- 20 years old in 2004, born 1983-84
- Lives in Halifax
- Online friend since summer 2003 (at the start of the friendship she was 18-19, Tegan was 16)
- Co-conspirator in Tegan’s vanishing plan
- Arranged a ride to pick Tegan up from the boathouse at 11 PM Aug 14 (whether Hannah was the ride or arranged a third party is open)
- Has spent the year since not knowing whether Tegan got cold feet, was caught, or was killed
- “h” — Tegan’s last text — was the first letter of Hannah’s name. Tegan was reaching for her friend in panic.
- The player will eventually message Hannah and reveal what happened. Hannah’s grief becomes coherent for the first time.

**Wren is bad but not the killer.**

- 19 in 2004, senior counsellor at Camp Pinecrest, four summers there
- Real predation of Tegan, real grooming, real coercion of Camille via Briar, real threats
- Has a history (Melissa, last summer) of similar predation
- **Wren did invite Tegan to the boathouse on Aug 14, but for an earlier meeting (around 9 PM, not 11).** They had a goodbye conversation, possibly a fight. Tegan told Wren she was going to leave camp / tell her mom (per Ch1 Aug 14 diary). Wren left. Tegan stayed at the boathouse to wait for her ride at 11.
- Built the Aug 14 alibi with Briar because she sensed something was about to happen and was scared of being implicated. The alibi was for *adjacent* crimes (predation, threats), not murder.
- Has spent the year since unable to grieve openly because grieving draws scrutiny she can’t survive
- Doesn’t know what happened to Tegan. May suspect she ran, may suspect she’s dead, doesn’t know.
- The “i’m not okay tegan” crack in her email is real. Wren genuinely loved Tegan in her own broken way.
- Wren does have access to Tegan’s account post-disappearance and edits diary files — including possibly the Aug 14 last entry. (See Ch2 realization beat.)

## The texts on Aug 14

The SMS log between Tegan and Hannah/Glorfindel is **all real**, no seeding. The player misreads the referents because they don’t know Tegan’s plan.

- “she wants me to meet her at the boathouse” — “she” = Hannah’s arranged ride, NOT Wren
- “she’s not here yet” — the ride is late
- “she’s STILL not here” — half an hour late, Tegan is nervous
- “wait. someone’s coming up the path. it’s not her.” — Tyler arrives, not the ride
- “h” — first letter of Hannah’s name, typed in panic in last seconds

Every text reads completely differently with this canon. The text itself doesn’t change.

